content.problemStatement:
The modulus operator (`%`) in C is an arithmetic operator that returns the remainder when one integer is divided by another. It is commonly used in remainder checks, loop cycles, and even/odd tests. In C, if the dividend is negative, the remainder takes the sign of the dividend.

**Syntax:**

```c
dataType remainder = dividend % divisor;
```
- `dividend` is the number to be divided and `divisor` is the number by which division is performed.
- The `remainder` is the result and is stored in the left-hand variable.

---

**Example:**

```c
#include

int main() {
    // Example 1: Positive dividend and divisor
    int dividend1 = 17;   // Dividend (positive)
    int divisor1 = 4;     // Divisor (positive)

    // Modulus operation returns remainder after 17 divided by 4
    int remainder1 = dividend1 % divisor1;
    printf("Remainder1: %d\n", remainder1);  // Expected: 1

    // Example 2: Negative dividend and positive divisor
    int dividend2 = -17;  // Dividend (negative)
    int divisor2 = 4;     // Divisor (positive)

    // Remainder will have the same sign as the dividend in C
    int remainder2 = dividend2 % divisor2;
    printf("Remainder2: %d\n", remainder2);  // Expected: -1

    // Example 3: Negative dividend and negative divisor
    int dividend3 = -17;  // Dividend (negative)
    int divisor3 = -4;    // Divisor (negative)

    // Again, remainder follows the sign of the dividend
    int remainder3 = dividend3 % divisor3;
    printf("Remainder3: %d\n", remainder3);  // Expected: -1

    return 0;
}
```

